Running style heuristics for post-initial worldline generation:

Front-runner / Nige:
- If there are few other front-runners, reduce early pressure and reduce unnecessary acceleration cost.
- In that case, increase late stamina retention and persistence.
- If the course is one-turn or has a long final straight, reduce the advantage of front-running because late runners have more time to catch up.
- If the course has many corners, increase front-runner persistence because repeated cornering reduces overall speed and helps conserve energy.

Stalker / Senko:
- Stalkers depend on the pace set by front-runners.
- If the race shape forces repeated acceleration to secure position, lower late stamina expectation.
- If pace is stable and running styles are naturally dispersed, increase stalker win probability.
- If similar stalkers are adjacent and ability is similar, inner position is advantageous due to lower path loss, especially on courses with more corners.
- On courses with few corners, inner-position advantage is weaker.

Closer / Sashi:
- Increase evaluation when front-runners and stalkers are likely to spend energy early.
- Increase evaluation on one-turn or long-straight courses because they have more time and space to improve late.
- Decrease evaluation on short-straight or many-corner courses because there is less time to close and more difficulty accelerating through turns.
- If there are few front-runners and pace is calm, reduce closer evaluation because leaders retain more energy.
- If many pace-pressuring horses exist, raise closer evaluation.
- On courses with many corners, wider draws slightly hurt closers because of path loss and delayed launch timing.

Deep closer / Oikomi:
- Strongly pace-dependent.
- Lower evaluation when early pace is calm or when there are few speed horses.
- Raise evaluation when early competition is intense and late front fatigue is likely.
- Raise evaluation on long-straight uphill finishes because leaders weaken more easily.
- Lower evaluation on many-corner courses because rear runners suffer more path loss and unstable lane access.
- On one-turn long-straight courses, allow stronger late improvement than standard closers.
